## Procedure

### Step 0: Locate plan root + slug

```bash
PLAN_ROOT="${CLAUDE_PLANS_DIR:-$HOME/.gstack/projects/$(basename "$PWD")}/tts"
[ -d "$PLAN_ROOT" ] || { echo "ERROR: /tts-design has not been run yet. Run it first." >&2; exit 1; }
echo "PLAN_ROOT: $PLAN_ROOT"
```

Ask the user for the TTS slug (must match an existing `/tts-design` output).
Outputs land at `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/`.

### Step 1: Verify base architecture is prosody-friendly

Read `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/ARCHITECTURE.md`. Some backbones support rich prosody surfaces
out of the box; others need bolt-ons; one or two won't carry it without rebuild.

| Backbone | Native prosody support | Style-token support (GST) | Reference-audio conditioning | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **StyleTTS2** | Strong (style diffusion) | Yes (style encoder) | Yes | Best canvas for accent + emotion control |
| **XTTSv2** | Medium (zero-shot style transfer) | Implicit via reference | Yes | Code-switch + cross-lingual native |
| **VITS** | Weak | Add GST head (extension) | Add (extension) | Needs work; OK for single-style + accent |
| **Tacotron2 + WaveRNN** | Medium | Yes (original GST paper) | Yes | Legacy; good for research replication |
| **Bark** | Native emotion tags (`[laughter]`, `[sigh]`) | No | No | Limited to its tag vocabulary |
| **Tortoise** | Reference-audio driven | Implicit | Yes | Slow inference; offline only |
| **F5-TTS** | Reference-audio conditioning | Implicit | Yes | Research license; flow-matching |
| **Piper / Glow-TTS** | Weak | No | Limited | Edge-only — accept flat prosody |

If the user's base backbone is in the "weak" row, AskUserQuestion:
- **Simplify:** "Your base TTS doesn't natively carry the prosody surface you want.
  We can either add the surface as an extension (more work, full control) OR switch
  the base to a prosody-friendly model (faster, but `/tts-design` rework)."
- **RECOMMENDATION:** B if expression scope is moderate; A if scope is heavy.
- **Options:**
  - A) Add GST + reference-audio extension to the existing backbone. Completeness: 8/10.
  - B) Re-run /tts-design with prosody-first constraints (likely → StyleTTS2). Completeness: 10/10.

### Step 2: Pick the control surface composition

The prosody-control surface is composed of 1-5 layers. Pick the combination per
use case.

| Layer | What it does | When to use | Cost |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Reference-audio conditioning** | "Style transfer from this clip" | Have clean style examples; want zero-shot transfer | Low |
| **Global Style Tokens (GST)** | Learn N latent style vectors from training data | Want categorical control ("happy/sad/teaching") with smooth interpolation | Medium (training) |
| **SSML extensions** | Explicit `<prosody rate="slow" pitch="+15%">` + custom `<style>` / `<accent>` / `<emphasis>` tags | Want author-controlled, deterministic output | Low (parsing only) |
| **IPA + tone marks** | Phoneme-level control with tone diacritics (Mandarin, Thai, Vietnamese) | Tonal languages, accent control, pronunciation fixes | Medium (g2p infra) |
| **Per-sentence style embeddings** | Compute style vector per utterance from text + tags | Long-form with shifting mood (audiobooks, explainers) | Medium |
| **Multi-speaker mixing** | Linear-interpolate speaker embeddings (e.g., 0.7·SpeakerA + 0.3·SpeakerB) | Voice blending, persona dial | Low |
| **Natural-language style prompts** | "Read this in a calm teacher voice" → embedded by an aux text encoder | Modern flow-matching models (F5-TTS, some 2024 SOTA) | High (extra model) |

AskUserQuestion (for each layer): include or skip? Show the cost + use case fit.

Write the composition to `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/CONTROL-SURFACE.md` with:

- One layer per section.
- For each: which technique, which library / config flag, what the user-facing
  control looks like (SSML tag? Style ID? Reference WAV path? Prompt string?).
- An end-to-end example: "User wants Thai-accented English in teaching cadence
  for sentence X. They call `tts(text, style='teaching', accent='en-th',
  reference_wav='samples/teacher-3.wav')` → here's how each layer activates."

### Step 3: SSML / tag vocabulary

If SSML or custom tags are in the surface, write
`$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/SSML-EXTENSIONS.md` defining:

- **W3C SSML 1.1 baseline:** `<break>`, `<prosody rate pitch volume>`, `<emphasis>`,
  `<say-as>`, `<phoneme>`, `<sub>`.
- **hstack extensions (custom):**
  - `<style name="...">` — references a GST token or a style embedding by name.
  - `<accent code="en-th">` — pushes the synthesizer toward an accent embedding.
  - `<cadence preset="teaching">` — preset that combines rate, pitch range, pause
    distribution.
  - `<repeat count="2" mode="exaggerate">` — for teaching cadence (repeat with
    increasing emphasis).
  - `<ipa>θa˨˩</ipa>` — explicit IPA with tone diacritics; passes verbatim to g2p.
  - `<lang code="th">` — code-switch boundary.

Each tag gets: syntax, attribute table, behavior, fallback when synthesizer doesn't
support it (graceful degradation, not silent drop).

### Step 4: Style data plan

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/STYLE-DATA-PLAN.md`. This is the augmentation
strategy to make the layers actually work.

| Layer | Data requirement | Augmentation |
|---|---|---|
| Reference-audio conditioning | 10-50 clean utterances per style (already in target voice) | None — keep clean |
| GST | 50-500 utterances per style, balanced across speakers | Speed perturbation (±10%), pitch shift (±2 semitones) — careful not to wash out style |
| SSML extensions | Test corpus where each tag is exercised + annotated ground truth | Synthetic — generate matched pairs by varying tags on same text |
| IPA + tone marks | Phoneme-aligned corpus; for tonal langs, tone-balanced | Forced alignment via Montreal Forced Aligner |
| Per-sentence style embeddings | Long-form corpus with sentence-level style annotation | Crowdsource style tags OR derive from emotion classifier |
| Multi-speaker mixing | Multi-speaker corpus with consistent recording conditions | Volume + RIR normalization |
| Natural-language style prompts | Paired (prompt, audio) corpus | Hard to augment; data quality > quantity |

For each row, also write:
- **Existing public datasets:** ESD (emotion), IEMOCAP (emotion), CSS10 (multi-lang),
  LibriTTS-R (clean multi-speaker), VCTK (accents), AISHELL-3 (Mandarin tones),
  Common Voice (breadth).
- **Custom data needed:** if the user's style set isn't covered (Hall's
  teaching-cadence Thai-accented English isn't on the shelf), spec the recording
  protocol — script list, prompt count, speaker count, hours target, mic spec.

### Step 5: Training plan addendum

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/TRAIN-ADDENDUM.md` covering:

- **Phase 1 (skip if base is already trained):** train base TTS per `/tts-design`.
- **Phase 2:** train style heads — GST embedding table, style encoder, accent
  embedding head. Freeze the base; train the heads only (much cheaper).
- **Phase 3:** joint fine-tune — unfreeze the last few layers of the base for
  the styles to actually shape acoustics. Small learning rate; risk of degrading
  base quality if overdone.
- **Phase 4:** train SSML tag parsers (if used) — these are usually rule-based,
  not learned; just write the parser.
- **Compute estimate:** typically 10-30% of base training cost for style heads.

### Step 6: Perceptual eval plan

Write `$PLAN_ROOT/{slug}/PROSODY/EVAL-PERCEPT.md`. Prosody quality doesn't reduce
to MOS alone — you need style-specific metrics.

Call `/voice-eval` with this metric set:

- **MOS / MOSNet** on neutral baseline (must not degrade vs base).
- **MOS-Style:** human listeners rate "does this match the requested style?" on a
  5-point scale.
- **Style classifier accuracy:** train a small classifier on style tags (or use
  emotion2vec); measure if the output's predicted style matches the requested one.
- **F0 distance** between output and reference style exemplar (for accent + cadence).
- **Duration distance:** RMSE of phoneme durations vs reference (catches cadence
  shifts).
- **Code-switch accuracy:** for code-switched outputs, WER per language segment
  (Whisper back-transcribe with language ID).
- **Accent panel:** native speakers of the target accent rate naturalness on a
  per-utterance basis.

S9 eval-store `task_id`s: `prosody-{slug}-{metric}`.

### Step 7: Hand-off

Print the file tree. AskUserQuestion:
- **Simplify:** "Prosody surface is designed. Next is either training (run
  `/finetune --domain speech-tts` with the addendum) OR perceptual eval if you
  already have a candidate model."
- **RECOMMENDATION:** A.
- **Options:**
  - A) Run /finetune to train the style heads. Completeness: 10/10.
  - B) Run /voice-eval against an existing candidate. Completeness: 9/10.
  - C) Stop — I'll review the plan first. Completeness: 9/10.

